On the other hand, what's the point of taking a medieval legend and making it exactly like a modern day action heist film? I don't despise innovation, but if you change too much you might as well drop ther pretense of making a "Robin Hood" movie.

text: This looks awful. They changed out so many elements of the core Robin Hood stories that they may as well have made an entirely new story & setting. Doesn't help that the clothes everyone wears look like Old Navy castoffs. The Sheriff looks like Grand Moff Tarkin, the city looks like it belongs in the Italian Renaissance, and if you wanted a diverse cast for a film set in Europe during the age of bows & swords then I can point to any number of vibrant port cities in the Mediterranean which would fit the bill better than "Nottingham."    Even worse it looks like four movies rolled into one cheesy premise. We have a vigilante hero story, a class warfare story, a casino heist film and then we have a guy called Robin Hood with a Bow who wants to steal. I get that Hollywood wants to play it safe and use an established premise rather than creating their own story, but isn't it more dangerous to put out B rated films that are almost certain to bomb?

James Cameron would roll over in his grave if he knew he could have worked on this movie instead of the 16 Avatar sequels he had planned. If this this isn't 3D we all will riot the streets wearing green. Imagine having an arrow coming right at you in the 3rd dimension. You would die. I'll die if they don't make this movie in 3D. I will purchase the 4K High Definition Box set with the collectable Robin Hood Figurines. It will be on my nightstand next to my bed and I will kiss it goodnight before I go to sleep every night for the rest of my goddamn life. I will say however, that they should have cast Russell Crowe. Why was this never done. Ridley Scott was too busy jerking off to Alien porn that he forgot to cast the God of Crows in a Robin Hood epic that would give any Gladiator to ever exist a sore rectum. The Academy Awards will be ransacked by this film. Robin himself would make an appearance, because this movie is real. Every Academy Award from 2018-3946 would be given to this movie because it would cause every volcano on earth to simultaneously erupt with pure semen. Roland Emmerich could not capture the magnificent scale of these volcano orgasms. He would, however, wonder why he never thought of a disaster movie staring Robin Hood himself to save the day. Who else would the scientists turn to in their time of need, but the King of Thieves? You can't destroy the earth if Robin steals the weather. I can see it now, 'National Treasure 3: King of Thieves.' "It's simple, we steal the ozone." Boom. $14 Billion right there. Easily. Nic Cage gets back on top like he has always deserved. text: For everybody harping on about this not being historically accurate...where did it say it was? I think this movie will be something like a Knight's Tale in its delivery as some people have already said but with more of a modern mash. And yeah maybe it won't be critically acclaimed, but it does look entertaining to watch and that's what matters in movies. You could have an awesome historical epic with everything right or at least most things but that's already kind of been done which is why they're putting a different twist on it here. If it's not your thing fine, Mary Queen of Scott's that's coming out in December looks more historically accurate and just as cool for different reasons  so you can see that ( i know i will!) but don't be judging other people because they're not hating a whole movie off of a 2 and a half minute trailer and historical accuracy when that's not even the goal here

This is a very poor visualization of the medieval era, and really disappointing.

More than that, I find it funny how some right-wing retards are whining about how they made a 'leftist' film, completely forgetting that Robin Hood was famous for taking money from the rich and giving them to the poor, just like 'dirty commies' do. text: Director Krennick survives Death Star's blast at Scarif and escapes to Earth, there, he forms his own "mini-empire" at Nottingham. He starts a new reign of terror.  There, a young boy called Eggsy gains his live at the streets by thieving to everybody, not the rich, nor the poor, everybody. One day, Eggsy steals something important to the greatest bounty hunter who has ever lived, Mr. Django Freeman. Then Django tracks down Eggsy's footprints and follows him to London, place where the young boy was selling this McGuffin. Django, angered by this, reclutes Eggsy to go with him in his own buissness. Django promises Eggsy to set him free until he pays what he debts or get killed, whateaver happens first. At this part of the story, we met the other raiders that eventually will for the outlaw group called The Kingsmen. Django trains Eggsy and teaches him the exquisite art of arrowing (Like if yoy catched the reference.) to prepare him with the struggle with Sheriff Krennick, who's power is getting bigger and badder. It is also revealed that Krennick's actions as sheriff caused Hildie's decease. That's why Django wants to kill and rob him. Django and his band starts to rob Nottingham's soldiers and Sheriff's men. Then they get the atenttion of our villain and start to get unsuccessfully hunted down. At the climax of the story, The Kingsmen, leadered by Django, sneaks into Krennick's house and steals all of his. The Sheriff then wokes because of this and starts to fight the thieves with his guards by his side. In the duel, Django gets hurted by Krennick's sword. Then Django shots Krennick at his british balls... This is for my Broomhilda, motherfucker!!! and bang. Krennick never talked again. The Kingsmen leave out the castle but they are intercepted by a bunch of furious pesants who heared all the noise of the castle. The crowd throws bombs to the thieves. Django gets hit by a bomb and killed in the process. Eggsy and the others miraculously escapes the scene. At the end, some weeks later, Eggsy and the other Kingsmen are travelling into the woods where they find a reward poster in one of the trees. The drawing in the poster is the one of Eggsy's face. "Robin Hood... Who the hell is Robin Hood!? I think it's your outlaw name. Do you think they'll put something like Eggsy? ...Robin Hood... I think I like it... hahaha, of course you dumbass, I told you!" Then, Robin and the others ride away leaving the tree and the poster.   THE END

text: Hollywood needs a hard kick in the ass. They can't even release a time period movie these days without resorting to "Sci-Fi / Marvel" special effects and lame digitally enhanced action. Not to mention that this looks like it took place in the 21st century with a few older looking props in the background. The problem with audiences nowadays is they relate more to fantasy than reality, which is why the Divergent series, the Marvel movies, The Hunger Games, and bullshit like this are dominating the market. Fuck movies suck nowadays, you can make a good time period action movie without making it completely unrealistic. This isn't Star Wars. Remember Braveheart and Gladiator? Hollywood needs to stop making movies that appeal only to the 12 - 20 year old kids and put something out that will satisfy us people 30 and up as well. Not going to hold my breath though. Welcome to the OVERLY DIGITAL age.

text: I've seen it. It's as bad as you think.  -Action is cut like a Marvel movie -Robin has his damn mask off half the time he's in battle and somehow his identity isn't given away -Yes, Marion is actually wearing that outfit in the movie. -Molotov cocktails in the era of Robin Hood where he fights in the Crusades. That happened -The comic relief friar character (Tillman was it?) is utterly lame -Robin gets an arrow TO THE HEART in the climax, Marion pulls it out, and he lives WITHOUT MEDICAL ATTENTION -Whoever directed this film thinks that a small trail of flammable fluid on the ground creates a huge inferno -John just "apparates" where the movie needs him to be. He's somehow on the boat back to England in the opening, then he's somehow masquerading as the Sheriff's guard in the climax (the last time we saw John before that scene, he'd found the room in the prison where the guards kept their armor. We don't even see how he made his way into the guard. We don't even know how he knew that Robin had willingly let himself be captured so that the Sheriff could have him executed. He's just...THERE) -Apparently the townsfolk call him "The Hood" because the director thinks that 13th century Englishmen have cool nicknames for noble people like him. -Nobody even attempts to talk Middle English. -There's basically a Canto Bight scene in the middle of the movie where they're gambling on 13th century roulette wheels and throwing weird-shaped dice and it honestly looks like some extravagant Vegas party. -For literally no reason, John forbids Robin from talking to Marion at the start of the movie...which gets forgotten within 15 minutes because after that point, Robin and Marion are having regular conversations and John doesn't give a shit.  The completely-not-subtle relation to Antifa doesn't even need to be mentioned. The rest of the film's bad enough.

text: I don't think this movie will do well, MAINLY because they chose Jamie Foxx.  But, once again those "social warriors" up in Hollywood in Socialist California feel the need to impose their ignorant views on the rest of us by making one of the main characters BLACK!  If you are going to remake or make a movie based on real events or people use those characteristics, ie, if the character or person was white LEAVE THEM WHITE!    I don't remember hearing about a Black guy in any of the Robin Hood books read or earlier movies made.  It's like making  a movie about the lives of Martin King Jr. or Malcolm X and making the characters WHITE! RIDICULOUS!  They would have been better off making one of Robin's "merry men" be a cyborg who was sent back in time! (maybe a sequel to the Terminator franchise?)    If Robin Hood was real, any evidence available shows he existed between the years 1150 and 1350. Therefore, BLACKS played NO role in English history when these events supposedly took place.  They were still in Africa with bones through their noses and chucking spears at lions and each other.   If they wanted to involve a Black guy, they should have made the setting in modern times, then MAYBE, and only maybe, would the movie made any sense or more profitable.  #tiredofsocialwarriors

The only negative in the comments below seems to be that everything isn't period-accurate, but honestly there were a LOT of movies made like this in 2018, where ancient periods were given modern twists so I'm not sure why all the anger about this one specifically. I'll update with a review after I watch it, but I can tell you I won't care at all about the fantasy mixed with the period. The Middle and Dark Ages were horrific and barbaric in real life so why would I want to have to revisit the worst of humanity in my lighter-side entertainment??

text: What the fuck. Coming back from watching the first couple minutes of the movie and they've got a commando squad of fucking long bows in an Iraqi looking village fighting terrorists. They'd NEVER have long bows in a village, they'd be fighting with swords no if and or buts. First seen and "robin hood" is wearing a button down shirt from 2008. Like, honestly, WHY EVEN CALL IT ROBIN HOOD. Make up a new story. Miriam, A THIEF?!?!?!??! SHE WAS A NUN!!!! WTF. I don't expect it to be spot on history class but Jesus Christ it feels like they're trying to re right history for all of the IDIOTS who eat this shit up! The first monologue says, "forget what you know about history, this is the REAL story." The fuck? I can't even watch this, I DON'T CARE IF THERE'S A BLACK GUY IN THE MOVIE. He's got NOTHING to do with the fact I think this revisionist fantasy BULLSHIT is bad. In fact, they mine as well of made the main character black and just made up a new fucking tale. WHO CARES!?!? The fact is this is utter shit, has NOTHING to do with the actual Robin Hood legends and I can't believe I wasted 5 minutes watching the beginning. Glad I stream this shit and never paid for it.  Lady Miriam the thief and Rob Hood the Navy Seal fighting terrorists in present day Iraq. That's what I got from the first 5 minutes. WOW.

The mix of time periods gives you those fantasy world vibes but the mention of historical events/actual places ties it to reality and in a certain way it matches Robin Hood because he actually existed, he is a real person, but his story is surrounded by legends so much that in a certain way, he has become a myth. His story sounds so much like a legend that ppl often forget he really existed. So yeah the mix between fantasy and reality in the setting matches the character so I found it a pretty good move on the producers part.

text: So for people that complain about the black character, i think there was a black in the original too with pretty much the same backstory. Also i think robin hood was pretty liberal so it's not weird that it has that whole antifa vibe. BUT the main issue with this movie is, since they were not about to make a medieval themed movie, WTF didn't they just simply made a robin hood futuristic remake? I mean they just made everything to seem modern with medieval stuff. For example, the scene with the horses could be a motorcycle scene, or the casino scene and mostly the final fight with the policemen/knights with globs instead of swords and square shields. They could name it something like "Robin Hood 2077" and it could take place in a post apocalyptic world were there is not electricity or guns and were  feudarchy came back and it would be much more interesting.
